:INFO
Knife Finishing: From 400 Grit to Mirror Polish
The post-heat-treat finishing progression determines the final look and corrosion resistance of the blade.

:PATH
Sanding Progression
Work through grits 220, 320, 400, 600, then 1000 for a satin finish.
|
:INFO
Sanding Progression
Begin at 220-grit to remove scale and grinding marks from heat treatment. Sand in one direction only until all marks from the previous grit are gone before moving up. Switch to 320, then 400, then 600. At each grit, rotate 90 degrees from the previous grit's direction so you can see when previous marks are fully removed. A 600-grit satin finish is practical and attractive for kitchen knives.

:PATH
Applying a Forced Patina on 1084
Coffee or mustard patina protects carbon steel and looks intentional.
|
:INFO
Applying a Forced Patina on 1084
Carbon steel (1084) will rust if left bare. A forced patina (iron oxide layer applied intentionally) slows future rust. After final polishing, clean thoroughly with acetone. Apply strong black coffee with a cloth and leave 30 minutes — this produces a gray-blue patina. Alternatively, coat with mustard and leave overnight for a dark mottled pattern. Wipe clean and oil lightly with food-safe mineral oil.

:NOTE
Handle Finishing Must Be Done Before Blade Sharpening
Shape and finish the handle before final blade sharpening. The abrasives used for handle finishing (sandpaper, files) will roll across the edge and damage a sharp edge if the handle is finished after. Sequence: handle shape → handle sand → blade sand → patina → sharpen → strop.
